The crew of the PN-9 devised a sail, cut from the fabric of the
lower wind, and made their way slowly to the southwest, in the direction
of Oahu and Pearl Harbor. On the eighth night they saw the searchlights
from Schofield Barracks and, on the next morning, the igland of Oahu. But
they were far to the north and the wind was forcing them west. That evening
the island of Kauai was sighted; they were well aware that the next island
was more than 1,000 miles beyond. As they were attempting to maneuver, a
submarine surfaced along side and soon took the the plane in tow for
Nawiliwili Harbor. The day was September 10; the PN-9 had been afloat for
nine long days.
